## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works but not cooperative | Can't unblock `GetNextItem()` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // Exit the loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log it, but you cannot
            // force-kill it. This is by design in .NET 8.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not shut down within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` silently compiles but throws at runtime**
It's still in the API surface (not `[Obsolete(error: true)]`), so your code compiles fine and explodes in production with `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

**2. Blocking calls won't respond to cancellation unless you thread the token through**
Your original `GetNextItem()` may block forever. You *must* refactor it to accept `CancellationToken`:
```csharp
// Before — blocks indefinitely, immune to cancellation
var item = queue.Take();

// After — throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
var item = queue.Take(token);
// or for async:
var item = await channel.Reader.ReadAsync(token);
```

**3. `volatile bool` is insufficient for cooperative cancellation**
`_running = false` can't wake a thread blocked on I/O or `Monitor.Wait()`. `CancellationToken` integrates with `WaitHandle`, `SemaphoreSlim`, `BlockingCollection`, and async I/O natively.

**4. `catch (OperationCanceledException)` without the `when` guard will swallow non-shutdown cancellations** — always filter with `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)`.

**5. There is no force-stop equivalent in .NET 8** — if your worker calls unmanaged code that hangs, your only option is `Environment.FailFast()` or running the work in a separate *process*. Design your `ProcessItem` to be cancellation-aware.

### If Using Hosted Services (ASP.NET Core / Worker Service)

Consider inheriting from `BackgroundService` — it wires up `CancellationToken` for you via DI and host lifetime:

```csharp
public class MyWorker : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
// Register: services.AddHostedService<MyWorker>();
```

This gives you graceful shutdown integration with the host for free.
